        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## Users-Per-Satellite Ratio Analysis — SpaceX Starlink Networks (as of March 31, 2026)\n\n### Source Disclosure (SpaceX S-1, filed May 20, 2026)\n\nPer the Prospectus Summary:\n- **Broadband network:** "approximately 9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in Low-Earth Orbit, providing broadband connectivity to approximately 10.3 million Starlink Subscribers across 164 countries, territories, and other markets."\n- **V1 Mobile network:** "our dedicated satellite-to-mobile constellation of approximately 650 V1 Mobile satellites provides satellite-to-mobile data, over-the-top voice, and messaging services to approximately 7.4 million monthly unique devices across approximately 30 countries."\n\n### Calculations\n\n**1. Broadband network (Starlink subscribers per satellite):**\n- 10,300,000 subscribers ÷ 9,600 satellites ≈ **1,072.92 subscribers per satellite**\n\n**2. V1 Mobile network (monthly unique devices per satellite):**\n- 7,400,000 monthly unique devices ÷ 650 satellites ≈ **11,384.62 devices per satellite**\n\n**Relative utilization:**\n- 11,384.62 ÷ 1,072.92 ≈ **10.61× more users per satellite on the V1 Mobile network** than on the broadband network.\n\n### Important Disclosure Caveat\n\nThe S-1\'s "approximately 9,600" figure is described as "Starlink broadband **and mobile** satellites," meaning the 650 V1 Mobile satellites are a subset of the 9,600 total. If one isolates broadband-only satellites (9,600 − 650 = 8,950), the implied broadband-only ratio would be:\n- 10,300,000 ÷ 8,950 ≈ **1,150.84 subscribers per broadband satellite**\n\nThe question\'s framing treats 9,600 as the broadband denominator, so the headline ratio of ~1,072.92 is reported on that basis. Either way, the order-of-magnitude gap between the two networks is preserved.\n\n### Utilization Implications\n\n1. **Asymmetric per-satellite load.** The V1 Mobile constellation supports roughly an order of magnitude more users per satellite (~11,385 vs. ~1,073). This is not evidence of over-utilization on the mobile side; rather, it reflects fundamentally different service profiles.\n\n2. **Bandwidth-per-user drives the gap.** Starlink broadband delivers median peak-hour download speeds of ~225 Mbps with ~25 ms median latency — a high-capacity, always-on, fiber-like service. Each subscriber consumes substantial downlink capacity, so the network needs many satellites per user. By contrast, V1 Mobile currently supports only "light data, text messaging (SMS), and over-the-top voice services" (e.g., WhatsApp, FaceTime) — low-bandwidth, intermittent, bursty traffic. A single V1 Mobile satellite can therefore serve many more devices because each device\'s capacity demand is a small fraction of a broadband subscriber\'s.\n\n3. **Different capacity-constraint regimes.**\n   - **Broadband:** capacity-constrained per user (each subscriber demands high sustained throughput). Utilization is measured in Mbps/Tbps per satellite, not user count. The planned V3 satellites (1 Tbps downlink each, ~60 per Starship launch) are explicitly aimed at relieving this per-user capacity constraint.\n   - **V1 Mobile:** coverage- and connection-count-constrained. The relevant metric is reach (devices served, countries covered, MNO partnerships — 30+ operators) rather than aggregate throughput. The ~10.6× higher user-per-satellite ratio is consistent with a low-bit-rate, high-reach service model.\n\n4. **Growth trajectory context.** The V1 Mobile constellation grew from ~360 to ~650 satellites since January 2025 (an ~81% increase) while supporting 7.4M devices — implying rapid device adoption per newly launched satellite. Starlink broadband subscribers grew ~105% year-over-year (from 5.0M to 10.3M) against a larger, more mature satellite base, indicating the broadband fleet is scaling to keep per-satellite subscriber load roughly stable while expanding total throughput.\n\n5. **Interpretive caution.** Users-per-satellite is a coarse utilization proxy. It does not capture (a) per-satellite capacity (which differs materially between broadband and V1 Mobile satellites), (b) geographic distribution of demand, (c) orbital geometry/duty cycle, or (d) the fact that "monthly unique devices" on the mobile side is a different unit than "subscribers" on the broadband side (a subscriber is a paying account; a unique device may be a transient SMS/voice session). The ratio is therefore most useful as a directional indicator of service-model differences, not as a direct capacity-utilization comparison.\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Network | Satellites | Users (as disclosed) | Users per Satellite |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Starlink Broadband | ~9,600 | 10.3M subscribers | ~1,072.92 |\n| V1 Mobile (satellite-to-mobile) | ~650 | 7.4M monthly unique devices | ~11,384.62 |\n| Ratio (Mobile ÷ Broadband) | — | — | ~10.61× |\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Prospectus Summary"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
